05377nam a22006855i 9789048501380DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20082009ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485013807 a10.1515/97890485013802doi  a(DE-B1597)534378  a(OCoLC)317798931  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a371.07709504aThe Madrasa in Asia :bPolitical Activism and Transnational Linkages /ced. by Yoginder Sikand, Farish A Noor, Martin van Bruinessen. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2008] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aContemporary Muslim Societies ;v200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgement -- tIntroduction -- t1. Voices for Reform in the Indian Madrasas -- t2. Change and Stagnation in Islamic Education: The Dar al-'Ulum of Deoband after the Split in 1982 -- t3. 'Inside and Outside' in a Girls' Madrasa in New Delhi -- t4. Between Pakistan and Qom: Shiʽi Women's Madrasas and New Transnational Networks -- t5. The Uncertain Fate of Southeast Asian Students in the Madrasas of Pakistan -- t6. Muslim Education in China: Chinese Madrasas and Linkages to Islamic Schools Abroad -- t7. From Pondok to Parliament: The Role Played by the Religious Schools of Malaysia in the Development of the Pan-Malaysian Islamic Party (PAS) -- t8. Traditionalist and Islamist Pesantrens in Contemporary Indonesia -- t9. The Salafi Madrasas of Indonesia -- tContributors -- tGlossary -- tAcronyms and Names of Organisations, Movements and Institutions -- tMaps -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aSince the rise of organizations like the Taliban and Al Qaeda, the traditional Islamic school known as the madrasa has frequently been portrayed as a terrorist hotbed. For much longer, the madrasa has been considered by some as a backward and petrified impediment to Islamic social progress. However, for an important segment of the poor Muslim populations of Asia, madrasas constitute the only accessible form of education and an opening to the wider world. This comprehensive volume presents a representative overview of the unknown world behind the walls of these institutions in nations such as China, Indonesia, Iran, and Pakistan, showcasing the educational changes and transnational networks that help to produce an alternative form of globalization.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aArmijo, Jackie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBruinessen, Martin van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHasan, Noorhaidi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNoor, Farish A, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNoor, Farish A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReetz, Dietrich, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSikand, Yoginder, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSikand, Yoginder, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWinkelmann, Mareike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZahab, Mariam Abou, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 avan Bruinessen, Martin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAUP eBook Package Backfile 2000-2013z978311070067108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Backlis